159067;instagram;2018-12-20 05:19:05;FALSE;ten years is a long time and yet it's flown by with not much in between. beginning of  2008- the world had everything to offer me.. until it didn't.  or at least
column2: i felt it no longer did.  april 2008 i was sexually assaulted by someone i knew and in succession i lost my best friend because she thought i was lying.  i temporally lost my family because they didn't know what had happened and why i was acting out. i was 18
column4: and now in an abusive relationship.  that leads to the picture on the left.  the time he burnt me with his blunt twice: the first because i wasn't behaving the way he wanted me to and the second because i didn't scream loud enough the first time.

column2: i had people in my life who intervened at this point and helped me escape and move on from that horrific time in my life.  i would love to say to you that i took full advantage of this opportunity and have succeeded in every aspect of my life
column3: but that wouldn't be the truth.  honestly
column6: and spiritually.  for the last 10 years i've been living life in a kind of fog
column7: moving and changing my life every time it became difficult in any way. i've also gained over 130 pounds.

column1: until this last month.  there was no big epiphany or life event
column2: but more of being tired of leading a life void of true happiness or valuable experience.  and honestly
column3: being this close to 30 is making me reevaluate things.  i want connection

column1: i know i'm not the only one.  in sharing honestly my struggles to regain myself and my eventual success
column2: my hope is i can inspire others in similar circumstances or at least help feel not so alone. life is so short
column3: this is our one chance to live it to our fullest. i no longer want to wish for things
column4: i want to make it happen. i'm going to be healthy
column5: i'm going to graduate college and university.  i'm going to make a difference in my own way.

column1: 159069;instagram;2018-12-20 05:19:21;FALSE;"huntington bank apologized this week for calling police on a black man who tried to cash his paycheck at a branch in brooklyn

the regional bank found itself on the defensive after a local news station relayed how ohio resident paul mccowns was treated on dec. 1 when he tried to cash his first paycheck after three weeks at a new job working for an electric company.

column2: a teller asked mccowns for two pieces of identification
column3: and he handed over his license and social security card. he then complied with being fingerprinted
column4: which is standard for nonbank customers trying to cash checks

column1: multiple tellers then debated whether the check was legitimate
column2: and after failing to reach his employer

column1: mccowns didn't realize the bank had also called police until he left and a squad car pulled up. after handcuffing him and placing him in the backseat
column2: police were able to reach his #employer and confirm the check was valid.

column3: who said he believes he was #racially profiled
column4: was able to cash his check at a different #huntingtonbranch the following day.

column1: in an emailed statement to cbs moneywatch

we sincerely apologize to mr. mccowns for this extremely unfortunate event. we accept responsibility for contacting the police as well as our own interactions with mr. mccowns. anyone who walks into a huntington branch should feel welcomed. regrettably
column2: that did not occur in this instance and we are very sorry. we hold ourselves accountable to the highest ethical standards in how we operate
column4: and interact with the communities we have the privilege of serving.""

column2: i'm 100 percent a feminist ğŸ’¥ my addiction to truth and truth seeking and truth telling hasn't just magically appeared from thin air. this is my rebellion against a childhood lost to lies and manipulative cruel selfish distortion (on the part of my father). my attitude isn't just #metoo
column3: but #iwonttakeanyshitfromyou. hence why i wrote an e-mail of complaint to my community mental health team last night off the back of the disaster that was last week's significant relapse and how services responded

column7: but i also know that a service should categorically not make the symptoms of an illness worse and a patients mental health presentation worse. if someone attended a&e with a physical problem and left in more pain

this is the type of retaliation women have to deal with when we stand up for ourselves. and i am filing a formal complaint against him for lying and antagonizing harassment.
i'm going to be strong and fight for my honor. this is for all the other fellow women who else have to deal with this type of harassment and retaliation

column1: 159402;instagram;2018-12-20 14:59:32;FALSE;"2018: i'll put a positive spin on you. .....

column2: you were a shit stirrer. you were the alchemist with a blow torch and a hammer. you snatched the comfort blankets off of me and so many of my friends
column3: igniting our own warmth. bloop! thanks for that.

column2: you brought #metoo to our throats then stood back as wailing cleared silenced voices. can you hear us now? we got our own psalms!! sing beautiful people. .

column3: you sunk health to all time lows
column4: you pulled back imaginations to reveal ignored realities
column5: you showed the strongest of these what grief feels like. you made our art stronger

column2: you brought us to our knees.

column1: ......and kneeling there we set our nicked swords down and through tears saw the blossoming of climbing jasmine and a bunny in the yard standing still in the full moon light. he looked to be praying. you brought us down to earth and back to poetry. simplify.

column2: an opportunity to devote my senses

column7: slushing over your brown pupil and silky hair

column1: damn the imagery  something i could have easily died for.

column2: we weren't one of those cheezy couples who'd demand the worlds' attention to satisfy their affection. we had our own way of keeping things subtle yet charming. i really adored the late friday night blabbers on the terrace where my head would be perfectly placed on your lap and you'd be busy caressing my hair. i'd boast my philosophical shit and you'd smile to every nonsense i'd ever said. this would go on for hours until the first light would strike our face and then our cold bodies would crave for the warmth of the bed.
trying to figure out the point where we went wrong. sometimes time and space do play a significant role in disordering the forbidden path. maybe

column3: i did see you by the metro in that same jacket i had gifted you on your birthday. my heart was racing. i didn't know what to do next. by the time i could figure anything
column4: our eyes met. but it was something different altogether. a bloom of awkwardness had flown in between our paths and we decided to take our ways

column3: cheeks all wet with tears and the situation was worsened by some continuous coughing.

column1: 159552;instagram;2018-12-20 17:48:29;FALSE;"if the song â€œbaby itâ€™s cold outsideâ€ were a movie scene in modern day it could easily be a horror. the original intention of the song didnt mean to be sexist or sexual harassment. in 1944 & 1946 it actually was just considered romantic for a love interest to not take no as an answer. to pursue no matter what and take what they wanted. however this sentiment and the lyrics havenâ€™t aged well. no means no means no. this attitude is not cute to replicate in modern day. also while the film that popularized this song neptuneâ€™s daughter made this song more about a woman being concerned about social judgement for her being our late with a man out of wedlock.... the â€œmale love interestâ€ grabs her roughly several times. pushes her down. pushes himself up against her. interrupts her speaking. itâ€™s very problematic. at the time though it was a step forward that was celebrated by women because it still was very rare to see women questioning society at all. itâ€™s complicated but as long as we donâ€™t glorify the physicality or promote the outdated flirtation tactics thatâ€™s key!

also! iâ€™ve launched a new series with @rosemcgowan called life as lyrics. we will be turning popular songs into movies scenes. we will remove the music and turn the lyrics into straight up dialogue. we want to address the fact that many of us have been lulled into being complicit towards the celebration of rape/violence/greed/selfishness/power abuse by masking the words with catchy beats. we donâ€™t need this kind of language to have good butt shake and head bob.

column1: 159754;instagram;2018-12-20 23:08:16;FALSE;"ğŸ’¥â¤ï¸ğŸ’¥ @regran_ed from @raindovemodel -  if the song â€œbaby itâ€™s cold outsideâ€ were a movie scene in modern day it could easily be a horror. the original intention of the song didnt mean to be sexist or sexual harassment. in 1944 & 1946 it actually was just considered romantic for a love interest to not take no as an answer. to pursue no matter what and take what they wanted. however this sentiment and the lyrics havenâ€™t aged well. no means no means no. this attitude is not cute to replicate in modern day. also while the film that popularized this song neptuneâ€™s daughter made this song more about a woman being concerned about social judgement for her being our late with a man out of wedlock.... the â€œmale love interestâ€ grabs her roughly several times. pushes her down. pushes himself up against her. interrupts her speaking. itâ€™s very problematic. at the time though it was a step forward that was celebrated by women because it still was very rare to see women questioning society at all. itâ€™s complicated but as long as we donâ€™t glorify the physicality or promote the outdated flirtation tactics thatâ€™s key!

also! iâ€™ve launched a new series with @rosemcgowan called life as lyrics. we will be turning popular songs into movies scenes. we will remove the music and turn the lyrics into straight up dialogue. we want to address the fact that many of us have been lulled into being complicit towards the celebration of rape/violence/greed/selfishness/power abuse by masking the words with catchy beats. we donâ€™t need this kind of language to have good butt shake and head bob.

column1: 159822;instagram;2018-12-21 01:16:43;FALSE;"the high priestess sits in front of a thin veil decorated with pomegranates. the veil represents the separate conscious and subconscious realms
column3: and serves to keep casual onlookers out. only the initiated may enter. the pomegranates on the veil are a symbol of abundance
column5: and are sacred to persephone who ate a pomegranate seed in the underworld and was forced to return every year.

column1: on either side of the high priestess stand two pillars
column2: marking the entrance to this sacred
column3: mystical temple (also associated with the temple of solomon). one pillar is black with the letter b (boaz
column4: meaning â€˜in his strengthâ€™) and the other is white with the letter j (jachin
column5: meaning â€˜he will establishâ€™). the black and white colours of the pillars symbolise duality â€“ masculine and feminine
column6: darkness and light â€“ stating that knowledge and acceptance of duality are required to enter this sacred space.

column1: the high priestess wears a blue robe with a cross on her chest and a horned diadem (or crown)
column2: both a symbol of her divine knowledge and her status as a divine ruler. in her lap
column3: she holds a scroll with the letter tora
column4: signifying the greater law (according to a. e. waite). it is partly covered
column5: signifying that this sacred knowledge is both explicit and implicit

column1: he did not retreat at the sound of deafening bombs.
he did not evade when foes surrounded him.
he banished everything that trickled a tear down motherland's cheek.

column1: as he sat down to exchange stories with his little daughter
astonishment caught him like a well executed strategy
and tortured him like a merciless enemy;
when he learned that his little one had a war to share too.
a one where she was at the frontline; vulnerable.
she froze at the mere sound of her enemies' footsteps
the iron heart that was impenetrable by solid bullets
now melted in the frightened flames of the littles one's tears.
behind muffled voices and stirring sobs
it was too many things on her plate.
the soldier shrunk in fear and insecurity.
had he really saved his motherland
as he sat on the bed
column2: warding off monsters under the bed

column1: it dawned on him that the monsters weren't under
but they were on the bed
he had saved the nation from danger
column2: but had he saved it enough?

column1: 1. there are literally thousands of recorded christmas songs out there; why do we have to hear wham!'s ""last christmas"" every hour on the hour? it has been scientifically proven to be the worst christmas song ever.
2. on a related note; are you telling me you can play that awful song 24 times a day
column2: but you can't work tom petty's ""christmas all over again"" or the kinks ""father christmas"" into the rotation anywhere?

column1: 3. ""greensleeves"" is no more of a christmas song than ""maryland my maryland"". just because a song shares its music with a christmas song
column2: doesn't make it a christmas song.

column1: 4. the charlie brown theme is not a christmas song either: even though we've developed a pavlovian response to think about christmas whenever we hear it.
5. at the risk of sounding anti-semitic
column3: jewish artists singing christmas songs irritate me. (looking at you manilow!)
